---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import ClaimCard from '../components/ClaimCard.astro';
import claimsData from '../data/claims.json';

const byId = (id: string) => claimsData.claims.find(c => c.id === id);
const gptbot = byId('gptbot-blocking-2023');
const mentions = byId('mentions-beat-backlinks');
const ghosts = byId('ghost-citations');

const title = 'Why AI doesn’t mention your brand: a diagnostic walkthrough';
const description = 'Four possible causes, checked in order: crawler access, indexation, entity presence and third-party corroboration. Each step is graded by how strong the evidence behind it actually is, not by how confidently it is usually stated.';

const faq = [
  {
    q: 'Why does ChatGPT or Google AI Overviews never mention my brand?',
    a: 'Work through four checks in order. First, can AI crawlers reach your site at all, meaning is GPTBot, PerplexityBot or a similar agent blocked in robots.txt. Second, is the page actually indexed by the search engines these systems draw from. Third, does your brand exist as a recognisable entity independent of your own website, meaning do other sources describe who you are. Fourth, is your brand corroborated by third parties the AI system already trusts, since being cited as a source and having your brand named in the answer are measurably different things.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Could blocking AI crawlers be the reason?',
    a: 'It is possible and checkable in minutes: look at your own robots.txt for Disallow rules against GPTBot, ChatGPT-User, PerplexityBot, ClaudeBot or Google-Extended. A dated study of the top 1,000 websites found roughly a quarter blocking GPTBot within two months of the crawler launching, so this is a real and common cause, not a theoretical one. It is also the easiest to fix and the first thing to rule out.',
  },
  {
    q: 'If my page ranks on Google, will AI Overviews cite it?',
    a: 'Decreasingly. Ahrefs found the share of AI Overview citations drawn from the organic top 10 fell from about 76% in July 2025 to 37.9% in January 2026 across 863,000 keyword SERPs. Ranking well is no longer a reliable proxy for being in the citation pool, because AI Overviews increasingly cite pages that rank for fan-out sub-queries the searcher never typed, not the original query.',
  },
  {
    q: 'My page is cited as a source but my brand is never named. Why?',
    a: 'This is a distinct, measured phenomenon called a ghost citation. Semrush’s study of 3,981 domain appearances across 115 prompts found 61.7% were cited as a source link without the brand being named anywhere in the answer text. If this is happening to you, the fix is not visibility, you already have that; it is whether your brand name is attached to the content strongly enough that an AI system reaching for it in a summary chooses to say it.',
  },
];

const schema = [
  {
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'BreadcrumbList',
    itemListElement: [
      { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 1, name: 'Home', item: 'https://geooptimised.com/' },
      { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 2, name: 'Why AI doesn’t mention your brand', item: 'https://geooptimised.com/why-ai-doesnt-mention-your-brand/' },
    ],
  },
  {
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'Article',
    headline: title,
    description,
    datePublished: '2026-07-14',
    dateModified: '2026-07-14',
    author: { '@type': 'Person', '@id': 'https://geooptimised.com/#sunny-patel', name: 'Sunny Patel' },
    publisher: { '@id': 'https://geooptimised.com/#organization' },
  },
  {
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'FAQPage',
    mainEntity: faq.map(f => ({ '@type': 'Question', name: f.q, acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: f.a } })),
  },
];
---
<Base title={title} description={description} schema={schema} ogType="article">
  <article>
    <header class="wrap pt-14 pb-8">
      <nav aria-label="Breadcrumb" class="data text-[0.7rem] uppercase tracking-widest mb-6" style="color: var(--muted);">
        <a href="/">Home</a> <span aria-hidden="true">/</span> <span style="color: var(--text);">Why AI doesn&rsquo;t mention your brand</span>
      </nav>
      <h1 class="font-display font-bold text-[2.2rem] sm:text-[3rem] leading-[1.06] max-w-[22ch]">
        Why AI doesn&rsquo;t mention your brand
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-4 data text-[0.72rem]" style="color: var(--muted);">
        By Sunny Patel &middot; 14 July 2026 &middot; Every statistic below is graded and sourced
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="wrap pb-10">
      <div class="border-l-4 pl-6 py-1 max-w-[66ch]" style="border-color: var(--accent);">
        <p class="font-display text-[1.32rem] leading-snug" style="color: var(--text);">
          There are four checkable reasons an AI assistant might not mention a brand, in the order to rule them
          out: crawler access, indexation, entity presence, and third-party corroboration. Most guides skip
          straight to the fourth and most difficult one. Check the first three first, because they are faster to
          confirm and easier to fix.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="prose-wrap pb-12 copy">
      <h2>Step 1: Crawler access</h2>
      <p>
        Can the AI system's crawler reach your site at all? Check robots.txt for a Disallow rule against GPTBot,
        ChatGPT-User, OAI-SearchBot, PerplexityBot, ClaudeBot or Google-Extended. If any of these are blocked, your
        content is removed from consideration before anything else on this page is relevant.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="wrap pb-12">
      <div class="max-w-[46rem]">
        {gptbot && <div class="fade-up"><ClaimCard claim={gptbot} compact={true} /></div>}
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="prose-wrap pb-12 copy">
      <p>
        That figure is nearly three years old and blocking has almost certainly grown since, not shrunk; we could
        not fetch a current, static, independently checkable percentage to replace it, and say so plainly rather
        than repeat an unsourced current-day number. The direction is not in doubt: deliberately blocking AI
        crawlers, whether for training-data or licensing reasons, is common and growing, and it is a binary,
        checkable cause. Test it before anything else.
      </p>

      <h2>Step 2: Indexation</h2>
      <p>
        If crawlers can reach the page, is it actually indexed by the engines these AI systems draw retrieval from,
        principally Google and Bing? A page can be fully crawlable and still sit outside the index, or be indexed
        with no ranking signal strong enough to surface for any query. This step is evidenced indirectly rather
        than directly: no study we found measures "not indexed" as a discrete cause of AI invisibility, because
        by definition an unindexed page cannot appear in any citation dataset a researcher could sample from. The
        practical test is the same one that predates AI search: search <code>site:yourdomain.com/the-page</code>
        on Google. If it does not appear, nothing past this step matters yet.
      </p>
      <p>
        Assuming the page is indexed, do not assume ranking position then does the rest of the work. Ahrefs found
        the proportion of AI Overview citations drawn from the organic top 10 fell from roughly 76% in July 2025 to
        37.9% in January 2026, and that most citations now originate outside it.
        <a class="link" href="/evidence/#citations-outside-top-10">Graded VERIFIED</a>.
      </p>

      <h2>Step 3: Entity presence</h2>
      <p>
        Does your brand exist as a recognisable entity independent of your own site, meaning do other sources
        describe who you are, what you do and how you relate to your industry, in language a machine can parse
        without visiting your homepage? This is the step where the evidence gets thinner. Ahrefs' correlation study
        is the strongest thing we found that touches it directly.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="wrap pb-12">
      <div class="max-w-[46rem]">
        {mentions && <div class="fade-up"><ClaimCard claim={mentions} compact={true} /></div>}
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="prose-wrap pb-12 copy">
      <p>
        Read precisely: web mentions correlate with AI Overview visibility roughly three times more strongly than
        backlinks do, but the study's own authors describe both correlations as "moderate to very weak" in absolute
        terms, and they measured correlation, not causation, on Google AI Overviews specifically, not AI search
        generally. This supports "being mentioned matters more than being linked to" as a direction. It does not
        support a confident claim about exactly how much it matters, or that a specific entity-optimisation tactic
        (a Wikipedia page, a Knowledge Panel, a structured entity home) causes a measurable lift. We found no study
        that isolates those tactics from the general mentions effect.
      </p>

      <h2>Step 4: Third-party corroboration</h2>
      <p>
        Is your brand named in places the AI system already treats as trustworthy, independent of anything you
        publish yourself? This overlaps with entity presence but is the step where citation and mention become
        measurably different outcomes, which is the finding most diagnostic guides skip past.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="wrap pb-16">
      <div class="max-w-[46rem]">
        {ghosts && <div class="fade-up"><ClaimCard claim={ghosts} compact={true} /></div>}
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="prose-wrap pb-24 copy">
      <p>
        In Semrush's sample, 61.7% of the time a page was used as a cited source, the brand behind it was never
        named in the answer text a user actually reads. If your analytics show AI referral traffic (a real, bankable
        signal) but you never see your brand mentioned when you test the same prompts yourself, this is the likely
        explanation, not a crawling or indexation problem. The sample is modest, 115 prompts, and Perplexity was not
        included, so treat the exact 61.7% as indicative rather than universal, while treating the underlying
        distinction (cited as a source is not the same as named in the answer) as well established.
      </p>

      <h2>Reading the four steps together</h2>
      <p>
        Steps 1 and 2 are binary and checkable in minutes: either the crawler can reach you and the page is indexed,
        or it is not. Steps 3 and 4 are graded, not binary, and the evidence behind them is real but thinner, mostly
        one or two large correlational studies rather than a body of controlled experiments. Work down the list in
        order. Spending on entity optimisation while GPTBot is disallowed in robots.txt is the single most common
        version of this mistake we encounter.
      </p>
      <p>
        For the wider evidence behind what does and does not move AI citation, see
        <a class="link" href="/how-to-be-found-in-ai-search/">how to be found in AI search</a>. For why a single
        visibility number will not confirm any of these steps worked, see
        <a class="link" href="/can-you-measure-ai-visibility/">can you measure AI visibility?</a>.
      </p>

      <h2>Common questions</h2>
      {faq.map(f => (
        <>
          <h3>{f.q}</h3>
          <p>{f.a}</p>
        </>
      ))}

      <div class="rule mt-12 pt-8">
        <p class="text-[0.95rem]" style="color: var(--muted);">
          Every statistic on this page is graded against its primary source in the
          <a class="link" href="/evidence/">evidence ledger</a>. We sell no GEO services. Our commercial interest in
          every tool we name is published on <a class="link" href="/who-pays-us/">who pays us</a>.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </article>
</Base>
